text: My Da grew up watching all the Godzilla films and to this day, still fancies them so he played them for me as well in the hopes that I would enjoy them as he does. Scared the bloody hell out of me at three years old when I first saw Godzilla vs MechaGodzilla (1974) and watched MG beat up Anguirus dressed like Godzilla. I cried because he sounded so scary and they seemed so real to me. = ) After some much needed comfort and hugs from my Da, I too have grown to fancy them and have been an admirer since. I can't stand the American rubbish from 1998 though. Leave it to the Yanks to ruin someone else's brilliance with their CG Godzilla and HORRIFIC ACTING version. I will probably wind up going with my Da to see this one. Looks ace, but again, it's an American version. Hope they do it justice this time. And Godzilla isn't Godzilla without fighting some other monster enemy, not the Yank military that always seem to win ¬†when no one else can. Pure tosh! Anyhoo, this looks rather ace. Can't wait for the next movie clip for more clues on what this one will be about. = )

text: Looks like it has the potential to be the Godzilla film which extends beyond the awesomeness of the visuals and goofy monsters (which I am a hardcore fan of. I am a Godzilla FREAK :D) and become something memorable. Sort of like how the original Jaws transformed the monster and shark monster movie genre. Plus, Gareth Edwards is an amazing storyteller, filmmaker, director etc. who is kind of independent and very unconventional with his stories and films. He is also an expert in VFX and is one of my favorite directors of recent years. His film Monster (or was it Monsters) were excellent! He said himself that this film wasn't at all shot like most major Hollywood films. It was, according to him, shot more like an independent film in away. I can't remember exactly what he said, but I trust in him man :) It would have been awesoem to see Neil Blomkamp be sort of in on this project when it comes to the visuals (not saying they are bad, it's just because Blomkamp is another expert on VFX and is also one of my favorite recent directors.)

Yes,¬†I know this¬†is¬†an effective way to create¬†hype/interest¬†for a¬†movie, but it often leads to high(too high) expectations of the fans, and when the monster finally appears on-screen and starts doing stuff.... People get disappointed because it wasn't what they expected.  The first teaser-trailer was mysterious, and that was good, because it was¬†just a teaser. But in a full trailer like this? text: Nice trailer. This trailer really plays like it's really trying hard to fight off the typical Hollywood trailer edit tropes, but it just can't quite shake them completely. But does well none the less.  I mean, compare this trailer with the Robocop trailer. Now that might seem some what unfair considering the Robocop "retake" is very clearly a delicate issue for many who enjoyed the original, but the way the Robocop trailer is edited is essentially ramming that home, saying to those people "yea your assumptions were right; this is going to be dumb".  Yet if you pick apart that Robocop trailer there are actually some interesting plot directions that could potentially make the actual film worth while. They are just not represented very well, in favour of "Hollywood dumb".

text: So, every news site I frequent is freaking the fuck out about this trailer. The ramifications this movie could have on the monster movie genre are huge, but I am skeptical. If you look at any REAL classic Godzilla film, it was more about the monster than it was about the all star cast. This trailer had a little too much cast for me, not enough monster. The phenomenon known as a Godzilla flick is based mostly around it's destruction of whatever city it is in and the futile fight of the puny humans trying to stop it. If this is another Godzilla 2000 then this franchise will die. IF they release another trailer then I hope they release a monster fucking shit up trailer and not a speech and damage trailer. SHOW US THE MONSTER!

text: Three Words: GODZILLA HAS RETURNED.  Hopefully they get these¬†thing¬†right in this movie that Roland¬†"Fuck-face"¬†Emmerich messed up in his movie:  1. Godzilla is Japanese, NOT FRENCH-POLYNESIAN. 2. It should take place in Japan. Sorry folks. NYC is getting to be the clich√© town¬†of monster/disaster movies. Plus, he rests the near the Pacific after getting his ass whooped, if you ever watch any of Japan's Godzilla movies they made. 3. GOOD ACTORS! NO SHITTY ACTING! 4. Feed him bugs if he is a lizard...(i know they probably wont do that bait scene, but its better than fish) 5. Make him look like the Godzilla from the 1980s-1990s but¬†with¬†CGI. That CGI Re-vamp in that 90s was terrible. Those guys did not watch Terminator 2 and that was released seven years before Godzilla or as I called it Shitzilla. 6. DON'T MAKE HIM HAVE KIDS OR HAVE HIM BE A HERMAPHRODITE! GODZILLA WILL ALWAYS BE A DUDE! 7. Bring the monsters from some of the old movies. I would be excited for Godzilla to go against Mothra but that is wishful thinking. 8. Use the lower-pitch growl sound. It is intimidating and menacing. High-pitched Growl? Not so much.  AND FINALLY.... 9. KEEP THE COOL POWERS HE GOT FROM THE RADIATION LIKE THE ATOMIC BREATH!  ¬†Finished the rant. Please Movie, do not fail me....

text: Okay. First please let me say that I had my doubts about this movie. I'm still pissed off at how crappy the 90s Godzilla movie was. I honest to God tried to block out the memory of how terrible it was. But after seeing this trailer, I am extremely impressed. I'm in love with how badass this Godzilla is! He's huge and has left nothing but destruction in his wake! His roar gave me chills! In fact just watching this trailer makes me want to watch all my old Godzilla VHS tapes. If this movie is successful my hope is that we will have Godzilla duke it out with other monsters again. Gosh those were the best! I cannot wait to see this movie in theaters!  But if this Godzilla lacks his signature atomic breath, you better believe I will start flipping tables.

text: I have never seen Godzilla as anything more than an incredibly intelligent animal. I hate stories where they try to make the big G anything like good or evil. He's not a hero, not an anti-hero, not a villain. He's a force of nature that simply goes where he wants and wrecks everything in his immediate area whilst doing so.  The best way to portray Godzilla is like an unbelievably territorial animal that attacks everything that challenges him on his turf. He just happens to consider the entire planet his territory. When Godzilla attacks other kaiju, it's cause they were trying to steal a slice of land for themselves. When Godzilla attacks humans, it's cause they keep building skyscrapers ON HIS PROPERTY!  Godzilla is the King of All Monsters. I bet that Godzilla keeps every kaiju on Monster Island so that he'll have subjects to beat down whenever he feels like enjoying a good old fashion tussle.

text: I'm not trying to be negative here but this trailer to me has me a little worried. Everything looks amazing, and Godzilla looks really really scary, however watching it several times has made me wonder the direction of the movie. Godzilla in the trailer to me really looks impersonal, and that is not what makes a Godzilla movie. A good Godzilla movie makes you identify with the creature, with Godzilla. In a Godzilla movie, Godzilla himself is a character who you are suppose to identify with. I think that's why the first American version of Godzilla did so bad in Japan. America didn't understand the mentality the Japanese had for Godzilla. He's not just some giant monster rampaging the city, this creature is for lack of a better term a person. In some Japanese movies Godzilla is clearly the good guy, in other he's the enemy. So when I look at this trailer I just see a monster. Don't get me wrong, a very scary monster, looks very impressive, but just a monster... I hope I'm wrong though. I hope this Godzilla actually gives character to the creature. :)

I wonder if we get to see him destroy the Golden Gate Bridge in this one, just like Ray Harryhausen's octopus from IT CAME FROM BENEATH THE SEA did. And they even have a character named Dr. Serizawa in this one... any relation to the one played by Akihito Hirata in the original? Godzilla is DA BOMB - both literally and figuratively speaking!

They sure as hell must have stopped having sex after the first time.¬† "That was great honey but I'm done now¬†unless you've got something more original. Cause people have been doin what we just did for years...."¬† Oh my even worse!!¬† Have they all run out of food cause it has to be new every time!!!¬† Water does after all get old after a few sips... Everyone who dislikes this video clearly has no sense nor respect for what Godzilla has accomplished over the decades, nor do they have any sense for why it is that he's such an icon. I admit that movie is, yes, a classic ‚Äì no one is arguing with you there. But we‚Äôre in 2014 and people nowadays want to better visualization, realism, and all-around bad-ass special effects. Movies like Godzilla and Star Wars were amazing visually during the time they were made and the technology that was available at that time. text: Ok, can I just clarify to people who only saw Godzilla 98 that this is not a squeal to that. This also has nothing to do with Pacific Rim. This is an American made Godzilla film with full on help with Toho, the company that started Godzilla franchise in 1954 all the way to 2004. This movie is suppose to have a far darker tone to original in 1954 film and is suppose to go back to the roots of what made Godzilla an indestructible force of nature and what he symbolizes. And to others who are either mad that they don't see the monster or any feelings to the characters, first its a teaser trailer, second you keep you audience in suspense by not showing the monster, for example Jaws, or the original Godzilla, until the halfway mark or towards the end. I'm just happy to see a real Godzilla film after 10 years, and to me this is how trailers are done. You don't give your entire movie away within 2-3 minutes. I'm just hoping it lives to all the hype I've been giving it after following this movie since 2010.

text: For those who don't know what a halo jump I'll explain. Ok usually when you are about to go into battle like a major battle if you saw the smoke that means that major is about to happen also High-altitude military parachuting (or military free fall (MFF)) is a method of delivering personnel, equipment, and supplies from a transport aircraft at a high altitude via free-fall parachute insertion. Two techniques are used: HALO (high altitude - low opening) and HAHO (high altitude - high opening).  In the HALO technique, the parachutist opens his parachute at a low altitude after free-falling for a period of time, while in the HAHO technique, the parachutist opens his parachute at a high altitude just a few seconds after jumping from the aircraft. HALO techniques date back to 1960 when the U.S. Air Force was conducting experiments that followed earlier work by Colonel John Stapp in the late 1940s[1] through early 1950s on survivability factors for high-flying pilots needing to eject at high altitudes. In recent years, the HALO technique has been practiced by civilians as a form of skydiving. HALO is used for delivering equipment, supplies, or personnel, while HAHO is generally used only for personnel.  In typical HALO/HAHO insertions, the troops are dispatched from altitudes between 15,000 feet (4,600 m) and 35,000 feet (11,000 m).[

The 1998 movie 'Godzilla' is not actually the real Godzilla, the Toho company has stated this often and he is known as 'Zilla'. Henceforth, this 2014 Godzilla movie has nothing to do with the 1998 movie.  Godzilla will fight other monsters in this film. Shit will be broken, Deal with it humans. text: On trailers like these, I like to look at the details and speculate  Main Trailer: 0:13 The airliner (Airbus A 380 or 340) appears that it made an emergency landing. Mechanical failure? EMP? Glancing blow? 0:25 Linear accelerator? Obviously some sort of underground science lab for physics.... 0:29 Same underground lab? Is it military, or is it civilian and the military is coming in? 0:36 Glancing blow by tail would be my guess, otherwise it would have been completely flattened. 0:40 prisoner? That glass partition, and he wants to "Talk to someone in charge". 0:44 If it is deep enough to pass under the carrier, it shouldn't be visible from the surface, especially if there is particulate matter and those search lights would create glare. Also, at that size, it should be crushed by it's own weight, especially on land. (Science SNAFU #1 and #2) 0:50 Thank goodness those destroyers were of to the sides of that dorsal spine. And that wave is going to cause problems.... 0:51 They're fucked 1:01 What is that fluid? That is radioactive waste that the USSR dumped, and it has a very nasty gash in it. Carried on land by Godzilla? Radiation doesn't cause mutations like this.... (Science SNAFU #3) 1:08 More than one creature, or just one? Judging from dialogue it can be guessed that they failed, yet we see the remains of one? 1:18 Shockwave is to slow, and sound comes on to early and shouldn't crescendo like that (Science Snafu #4) 1:25 Big gun? EM railgun? 1:28 Human weapon, or Godzilla eggs? Construction BY Godzilla? 1:29 Vessel or base? 1:31 Something big diving followed by the jets. thank you +Sandwichman1337 for pointing that out. I missed that on my first run through. 1:33 Three USMC assault carriers, so the jets are probably F-35Bs, soon to be used by the United States Marine Corps (Ooh-rah) 1:36 HALO jump. Spotters for artillery or do they have a¬† special weapon? 1:40 Civilian bunkers? 1:44 obviously they can be killed 1:47 Golden Gate. San Francisco. 1:50 The military jets were in flat spins, meaning stalls. I am guessing that they get a very nasty tailwind or glancing blows. EMP or mechanical failure are not likely because they should glide, and I saw an F-35 [probably a B model (I hope to get my hands on one of those) because of the lines on the back of the fuselage at 1:53] pilot punch out. 1:53 Canopy is still closed, so somebody didn't punch out.... Why? Pilot error or mechanical? Or is the pilot incapacitated (High G spins can knock you out)? 2:03 Signal flares. Danger close? 2:11 That Blackhawk has an engine fire and tail rotor failure (judging from direction of spin) 2:18 That classic roar and title....Ôªø  Teaser: 0:01 HALO jump means close-quarters action, so I expect that they have a weapon. 0:15 A whole platoon? 0:28 C-17 Globemaster III. Smoke flares to prevent collision with other jumpers. Also, for that cargo bay, it should be wider if it is a C-17. 0:47 Electrically charged smoke? I see a fair sized risk of the jumpers getting struck. 1:19 I still think that is a Linear accelerator. Obviously some sort of underground science lab for physics, either military or civilian. 1:20 What is the purpose of the train? Probably not armoured because it won't make a difference, but would probably set it down. And why a cargo train? 1:27 Obviously a military bunker 1:28 HAZMAT suit. Bio, chem, or nuclear weapon? 1:32 Crashing, or simply exploding on the tarmac? 1:34 What the fuck is that? nuclear torpedo? Suicide nuke for the ship to ram with? Some other weapon? 1:38 Underground or on a ship? Again, why HAZMAT? 1:40 Yeah, armor on the train won't help.... And that train is FUBAR.

text: I don't understand why so many people are saying that they stole the theme from 2001: A Space Odyssey! The song is over 100 years old and has been used in numerous shows, movies and commercials. You could say that the makers of 2001 stole "Also Sprach Zarathustra" from Richard Strauss. It's not like he wrote it back in 1896 for that one movie. I'm sure the film's composer, Alexandre Desplat, searched long and hard for the perfect¬†accompaniment for that scene. Can you think of anything that would be more fitting? I can't.

text: I feel this trailer set a much different tone for Godzilla than the movie actually did. In this trailer, Godzilla is set out to look like the big scary beast that no one has ever dealt with before and the one who caused much of the destruction of the city. But in the movie Godzilla is clearly set as a less grey protagonist who we feel no fear for appearing which I was kind of disappointed about. But for the type of movie it ended up being I still enjoyed very much, it was just different than what I thought. Perhaps this is just an introduction movie to hype up for possible sequels?

text: You can be disappointed or not, fact is the general consensus of the movie was positive and it crushed in the box office. This means there will be a sequel which they announced and the overall general public who liked the movie are completely on board for a sequel. I just think you need more prolonged scenes with Godzilla and not half assed ones in the 2014 reboot. I personally think they should make him a bit meaner, a bit leaner, and improve his atomic breath's power(as cool as the scene was, the actual power of true Godzilla atomic breath at that range¬†would have¬†and SHOULD have sent the Mutos flying across state lines. Ok that's a bit exaggerated but I think you get the point. Im not asking for final wars orbit atomic breath, or meteor stopping atomic breath(although it is possible if Godzilla actually existed) but something that packs a bit more punch especially at that range. Overall it was a good movie and it catered more to the youth of today to reinvigorate Godzilla. From a Marketing standpoint this movie was pure genius. From and old school fan such as myself it could have been better. However if you find me one single kid under the age of 15 that didn't like this movie, then either¬†1 your lying or 2 your a fool.

text: I don't understand why most people hated it. Although it wasn't the best action/sci-fi movie compared to the other options available, Godzilla wasn't too terrible as reviewed.¬†  1. Godzilla's appearance. Yes, Godzilla got a little screen time as hoped but it was for a valid reason. The movie portray Godzilla as nature's weapon against enormous creature. Its a basic logic of food chain. There can only be one predator who can be dominant. Godzilla, who had stayed dominant for years, needs to establish his power. Thus, acts like a predator, tracking his prey and coming in for the sneak attack. Of course he is not going to get a lot of screen time! He being late for the party makes him adds more to his bad-ass character.¬†  2. As for the characters, I felt that it was imperative that they kill off the scientist. In most sci-fi movies, it is the crazy maniac that drives the plot and the search for the solution to the conflict. The father dying was important for the son to gain closure and understanding of the truth of the creatures. Plus, because of his death, the story line became more original. It became a story of a soldier trying to get home to his family in midst of a crisis. He was willing to do whatever it takes to do so. Everyone else were simply bystanders to nature's course.¬†  3. Military's failure to learn their lesson. The Japanese scientist mentioned that man's arrogance is that they think they can control/dominate nature. This movie depicts that very arrogance. ¬†They don't trust what they don't know. They use whatever they have at their disposal to take care of a threat. They think they are powerful enough to take care of any threat. Thus, they continue to do stupid mistakes because they are incapable of thinking beyond their ego and understanding that their power is limited compared nature. Their mistakes and put into positions where they are powerless was to show how little we are compared to the forces of nature.¬†  Overall, I thought the movie did an okay job of displaying the theme- humans are not as powerful as they seem to be. Nature can take care of itself and should not be tampered with. Switching the perspective from a scientist searching for answers to a soldier. It ¬†made the movie original. A soldier trying to get to his family added a more human element to the mix which made it all the more enjoyable. The action sequences were intense and never a let down. The ending where Godzilla collapses out of exhaustion was realistic and I'm glad they added it. The movie was not a complete letdown as made out to be.

text: This movie is both a gift and a curse.¬†Despite conflicting reviews, many of¬†the films strongest elements, from its¬†direction, cinematography,¬†visual effects, creature designs, sound design, and seemingly serious tone, were just enough to win many fans over. Had it not been for this movie, Toho probably wouldn't have come back to make "Godzilla 2016," let alone let¬†Rodan, Mothra, and King Ghidorah¬†be included in the sequels. As¬†far as I know,¬†it can only go up from here for the franchise.  On a bad day,¬†I think¬†this movie is living proof that Hollywood still thinks Godzilla fans are completely and utterly worthless. But on a good day, this movie is a¬†treasured¬†milestone that encompasses how far I've come as a lifelong fan. One that I'll always cherish as a nostalgic memory.  Hail to the king, baby!

text: Still one of the greatest trailers in history. The movie didn't fully live up to it, but still solid, gorgeous mayhem on an epic scale. Gareth Edwards is visionary, but I think he should have co-written it, because he could have added the necessary humanity to most of the flat human characters. The Brody's were solid (Cranston the best, obviously), but Taylor-Johnson's Ford was good, just not an emotional powerhouse like Cranston, which I found to be kinda funny since Elle (Elizabeth Olsen) was much more emotional than Ford. I just hope they address those mistakes in the sequel, all the while giving Gojira even more screen time, because sorry to the sad haters, but his screentime here is 100% justified, because it was about the same amount as in the original, having the slow-build to his reveal, and human scientists bandying back and forth while s**t hits the fan.

text: It took me over 3 years to get over the disappointment of this movie, but I am so glad I eventually did because now I fucking love it.  Still though, I think the trailer is actually better than the movie, but this is one of the best trailers I have ever seen. I actually have a theory about this trailer and how it had an impact on the final movie so if you want to hear it, bare with me.  So in this first trailer we see a few shots.The Halo Jump shows Godzilla slowly walking through the city as the troops fall. The Airport scene where the train breaks (I am not sure if it is actually different but in this it looks like Godzilla's hand going through it.) And also the planes exploding which does not show any monsters. Finally there is the shot of Godzilla concealed by dust and debris.  Each of these shots were changed (In the case of the last one, removed) for the final cut of the movie. Even in the official trailer when Elle Brody is going into the bunker, we see only Godzilla roaring and in the movie it is changed again to include the Muto. Now what I think may have happened is that when people seen this, they were excited, but did not want a repeat of '98. They did not want the military to kill Godzilla, but also the writers didnt want him to destroy everything and not have room for a sequel. So then people wanted more monsters so as to make it feel more like a Godzilla film. I think Godzilla was originally intended to be the bad guy. I think he was going to be the one who was going to attack humanity and it was up to us to stop him. Which I feel would have been the absolute best way to go about it, sort of like '84 but with a different ending.    Now I could be wrong and in all likelihood I probably am, but still, I kind of like to think about it xD

text: Great (misleading) trailer for an otherwise dull and not to special Godzilla movie.  When I saw this trailer I thought an American Godzilla movie finally done right.  The trailer made the movie look dark, and that it was going to bring Godzilla back to being the wrath of mankind's nuclear destruction.  Well the end result was some of that, but mostly just another monster vs. movie with a generic monster(s) in the Muto's, and boring lead character in Ford, and hardly any Godzilla until the last thirty or so minutes.    To say I was underwhelmed by the final product would be an understatement.  I only had to wait 2 years until Shin Godzilla came out which was more like the Godzilla movie I wanted to see, so I guess I can't complain too much. I get people liked Godzilla 2014 and that's fine, it's hardly the worst Godzilla film, but for my anticipation going in, it did nothing for me personally.

text: Can we all just admire how flawless this teaser is?  It hits all the right notes keeping you enticed without spoiling anything, it always invokes a haunting feeling inside of you, it still sticks with you if you were lucky enough to see it back in 2013 - it's everything that makes a teaser an ACTUAL TEASER. New Godzilla fans are currently living in an incredible time.
